another 8 cases I have that you can try.

```python
from typing import Optional
import io
import torch
import copy
import onnxruntime
import onnx
import itertools

_ORT_PROVIDERS = ["CPUExecutionProvider"]

def convert_to_onnx(
    model,
    input=None,
    opset_version=9,
    do_constant_folding=True,
    keep_initializers_as_inputs=True,
    dynamic_axes=None,
    input_names=None,
    output_names=None,
    fixed_batch_size=False,
    training=None,
    verbose=False,
):
    f = io.BytesIO()
    input_copy = copy.deepcopy(input)
    torch.onnx._export(
        model,
        input_copy,
        f,
        opset_version=opset_version,
        do_constant_folding=do_constant_folding,
        keep_initializers_as_inputs=keep_initializers_as_inputs,
        dynamic_axes=dynamic_axes,
        input_names=input_names,
        output_names=output_names,
        fixed_batch_size=fixed_batch_size,
        training=training,
        verbose=verbose,
    )

    print(" === Checking ONNX === ")
    m = onnx.load(f)
    a = onnx.shape_inference.infer_shapes(m, True, True)
    #onnx.checker.check_model(m)
    print(" === Check Ended === ")

    # compute onnxruntime output prediction
    so = onnxruntime.SessionOptions()
    # suppress ort warnings.
    # 0:Verbose, 1:Info, 2:Warning. 3:Error, 4:Fatal. Default is 2.
    so.log_severity_level = 0
    ort_sess = onnxruntime.InferenceSession(f.getvalue(), so, providers=_ORT_PROVIDERS)
    return ort_sess

class IfNoneInput(torch.nn.Module):
    def forward(self, x) -> Optional[torch.Tensor]:
        y: Optional[torch.Tensor] = None
        if x.size(0) > 1:
            y = x
        return y

class IfNoneOutput(torch.nn.Module):
    def forward(self, x) -> Optional[torch.Tensor]:
        y: Optional[torch.Tensor] = x
        if x.size(0) > 1:
            y = None
        return y

class LoopNoneInput(torch.nn.Module):
    def forward(self, x) -> Optional[torch.Tensor]:
        y: Optional[torch.Tensor] = None
        for _ in range(x.size(0)):
            y = x
        return y

class LoopNoneOutput(torch.nn.Module):
    def forward(self, x) -> Optional[torch.Tensor]:
        y: Optional[torch.Tensor] = x
        for _ in range(x.size(0)):
            y = None
        return y

module_classes = [IfNoneInput, IfNoneOutput, LoopNoneInput, LoopNoneOutput]
x_sizes = [0, 1]

# Need scripting to preserve control flow for this test to be
# meaningful.
for (module_class, x_size) in itertools.product(module_classes, x_sizes):
    model = torch.jit.script(module_class())
    f = io.BytesIO()
    x = torch.ones(x_size)
    dynamic_axis_name = "condition"

    convert_to_onnx(
        model,
        x,
        opset_version=16,
        # Ensure condition is not constant
        dynamic_axes={"x": {0: dynamic_axis_name}},
        input_names=["x"],
    )
```

issue.title: Skip Constant Folding for ops producing an optional type output

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Description**: Optional tensors that contain data are tensors at runtime and hence the check that an output OrtValue of an op be a tensor before deciding whether to constant fold the op is not correct. Instead, make the decision based on the proto type of the output NodeArg and ensure that the type is of type tensor before going ahead with constant folding. 

**Motivation and Context**
Fixes https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/11717

Hi Hari,
Most of the test cases pass, but this one error out during inference with the message:
```bash
sess = C.InferenceSession(session_options, self._model_bytes, False, self._read_config_from_model)
onnxruntime.capi.onnxruntime_pybind11_state.Fail: [ONNXRuntimeError] : 1 : FAIL : Node (Loop_5) Op (Loop) [TypeInferenceError] Output was expected to have tensor type. Got 9
```
It can be exported though,
```python

class LoopNoneInput(torch.nn.Module):
    def forward(self, x) -> Optional[torch.Tensor]:
        y: Optional[torch.Tensor] = None
        for _ in range(x.size(0)):
            y = x
        return y

# x_size = 0, 1 are both tested
# x_size = 1
x_size = 0

model = torch.jit.script(LoopNoneInput())
f = io.BytesIO()
x = torch.ones(x_size)
dynamic_axis_name = "condition"

torch.onnx.export(
    torch.jit.script(model),
    (x,),
    f,
    opset_version=16,
    # Ensure condition is not constant
    dynamic_axes={"x": {0: dynamic_axis_name}},
    input_names=["x"],
)
```
Let me know if you need more information.

This error message is coming from ONNX - specifically the Loop's type inference function - https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/a525f98d5ed31660b629bab90c680a39658a5c08/onnx/defs/controlflow/defs.cc#L250. 

One would have to look into what is specifically wrong with the model but I am guessing that when this is invoked -  https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/a525f98d5ed31660b629bab90c680a39658a5c08/onnx/defs/controlflow/defs.cc#L337, it eventually runs into this - https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/a525f98d5ed31660b629bab90c680a39658a5c08/onnx/defs/shape_inference.cc#L343.

I am thinking there is an issue with some type info in the model you are running into this issue with.
The remaining issue seems to be from shape inference about loop node. I will reopen this issue if I find any issue later.
Re-opening since the fix hasn't been merged.
